1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:02,500
<i>Previously on Desperate Housewives:</i>

2
00:00:03,100 --> 00:00:10,500
I would love her like she is my own!

3
00:00:10,501 --> 00:00:11,501
<i>Lynette made a promise.</i>

4
00:00:11,502 --> 00:00:12,502
His wife goes missing 
and his mistress turns up dead?

5
00:00:11,100 --> 00:00:13,400
I just can't believe that
Orson could do such a thing.

6
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:14,700
<i>Mike got arrested...</i>

7
00:00:14,800 --> 00:00:17,300
Oh, thank God!
- <i>and a friendship hit the rocks.</i>

8
00:00:17,300 --> 00:00:19,800
I am not playing with a woman
that is willing to let Mike

9
00:00:19,800 --> 00:00:21,000
take the fall for her psycho husband.

10
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:22,300
<i>Susan made a deal.</i>

11
00:00:22,300 --> 00:00:25,000
<i><i>(Ian)</i></i> I'll hire the best lawyer
in town, on one condition--

12
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:26,500
you can't see him anymore.

13
00:00:26,500 --> 00:00:28,200
<i>And a missing wife returned.</i>

14
00:00:28,200 --> 00:00:29,200
Hello, Alma.

15
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:37,100
<i><i>(Mary Alice)</i> To understand
the journey of Alma Hodge,</i>

16
00:00:37,200 --> 00:00:40,700
<i>you first need to know
how it started.</i>

17
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:44,500
<i>It began the day
she wed Orson Hodge,</i>

18
00:00:44,600 --> 00:00:47,300
<i>a man she had
tricked into marriage</i>

19
00:00:47,300 --> 00:00:49,500
<i>by getting pregnant.</i>

20
00:00:49,500 --> 00:00:53,200
<i>Alma was confident
that as their family grew,</i>

21
00:00:53,300 --> 00:00:55,900
<i>Orson's feelings for her
would grow as well.</i>

22
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:59,300
<i>But then
something went wrong,</i>

23
00:01:00,200 --> 00:01:04,100
<i>and the baby she had been
counting on never came.</i>

24
00:01:05,100 --> 00:01:08,200
<i>So Alma found herself
married to a man</i>

25
00:01:09,300 --> 00:01:11,100
<i>who seemed to despise her.</i>

26
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:16,300
<i>Still, Alma hoped
things would get better...</i>

27
00:01:16,800 --> 00:01:20,500
Mama loves her baby.
Does the baby love mama?

28
00:01:20,500 --> 00:01:22,400
<i>until the day she discovered</i>

29
00:01:22,400 --> 00:01:26,700
<i>Orson was having an affair.</i>

30
00:01:26,700 --> 00:01:28,400
<i>And Alma realized</i>

31
00:01:28,400 --> 00:01:31,900
<i>the only way she'd ever get
her husband to appreciate her</i>

32
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:33,900
<i>was to leave him...</i>

33
00:01:34,700 --> 00:01:36,400
<i>immediately.</i>

34
00:01:47,100 --> 00:01:49,400
If you don't get back
in your cage right now,

35
00:01:49,500 --> 00:01:52,600
I'm gonna have
to leave you behind. Please!

36
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:14,900
Going somewhere?

37
00:02:15,700 --> 00:02:17,600
I'm staying
at a motel tonight.

38
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:20,600
Why?

39
00:02:20,800 --> 00:02:23,700
I don't have time to discuss it.
I'm late for the bus.

40
00:02:25,800 --> 00:02:26,400
All right.

41
00:02:35,700 --> 00:02:37,500
I'm going away because...

42
00:02:37,700 --> 00:02:40,500
I know you're having
an affair.

43
00:02:40,500 --> 00:02:42,400
Ah. I see.

44
00:02:42,400 --> 00:02:45,500
Aren't you even
gonna deny it?

45
00:02:45,500 --> 00:02:47,500
On the contrary.

46
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:50,100
I wanna shout it
from the rooftops!

47
00:02:50,100 --> 00:02:53,400
For the first time in my life,
I'm actually in love.

48
00:02:53,400 --> 00:02:56,500
How can you say that to me?
I'm your wife!

49
00:02:56,500 --> 00:02:59,200
We both know
why we got married,

50
00:03:00,100 --> 00:03:02,600
and it had nothing
to do with affection.

51
00:03:02,600 --> 00:03:05,700
So you don't care if I go?

52
00:03:06,900 --> 00:03:07,900
No.

53
00:03:13,400 --> 00:03:15,900
Wait! This isn't
what's supposed to happen!

54
00:03:15,900 --> 00:03:18,000
You should be begging me
to stay with you.

55
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,800
I deserve to be happy, Alma.
So do you.

56
00:03:21,100 --> 00:03:23,700
And we're clearly
not gonna find that together.

57
00:03:23,900 --> 00:03:25,800
Orson, no!

58
00:03:26,100 --> 00:03:28,100
<i>it was at that moment</i>

59
00:03:28,100 --> 00:03:32,900
<i>Alma realized it wasn't enough
to leave her husband.</i>

60
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:36,500
<i>he had to be punished.</i>

61
00:03:36,500 --> 00:03:41,800
<i>yes, this was the journey
of Alma Hodge...</i>

62
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:45,400
Bree Hodge?
I'm Alma Hodge.

63
00:03:45,400 --> 00:03:47,900
I believe we have
someone in common.

64
00:03:51,900 --> 00:03:55,700
<i>and it wasn't over yet.</i>

66
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:15,300
<b><i>Desperate Housewives 3x11
"No Fits, No Fights, No Feuds"</i></b>

67
00:04:37,900 --> 00:04:42,300
<i>There is a time of day
all housewives look forward to.</i>

68
00:04:42,400 --> 00:04:46,300
<i>It occurs just after
the chores have been completed</i>

69
00:04:46,300 --> 00:04:49,400
<i>and right before the children
come home from school.</i>

70
00:04:51,700 --> 00:04:54,900
<i>It's a time for good friends
to get together,</i>

71
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:59,400
<i>have a cup of coffee
and exchange gossip</i>

72
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:03,100
<i>about the other good friends
who couldn't make it that day.</i>

73
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:05,300
Bree let her son
move back in.

74
00:05:06,400 --> 00:05:08,000
You're kidding. When?

75
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:11,000
Yesterday.
I'm so disappointed in her.

76
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:12,700
well, the police
did arrest Mike.

77
00:05:12,700 --> 00:05:14,700
I mean, I know
you think he's innocent,

78
00:05:14,700 --> 00:05:15,800
but surely you can understand

79
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:17,600
why Bree's feelings
have changed.

80
00:05:17,900 --> 00:05:18,800
Well, mine haven't,

81
00:05:19,100 --> 00:05:21,800
and I know something
that Bree probably doesn't.

82
00:05:25,700 --> 00:05:28,400
When Orson was 17,

83
00:05:29,300 --> 00:05:31,400
he spent time
in a mental institution.

84
00:05:31,500 --> 00:05:32,800
How did you find that out?

85
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:35,900
I snuck into his office
and rifled through his things.

86
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:39,600
Of course you did.
But that doesn't prove

87
00:05:39,700 --> 00:05:41,200
he had anything to do
with Monique's murder.

88
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:43,300
No, but it's a piece
of the puzzle.

89
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:45,800
<i>I mean, he did
have an affair with her.</i>

90
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:47,300
And when you combine that

91
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:49,000
with the fact that
his first fe went missing...

92
00:05:53,900 --> 00:05:55,300
So you're Alma.

93
00:05:55,300 --> 00:05:57,300
Where have you been
all this time?

94
00:05:57,600 --> 00:05:59,400
In Canada.
My aunt lives there.

95
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:01,200
Well, you should've
told someone.

96
00:06:01,200 --> 00:06:03,000
People thought
you were dead.

97
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:05,300
Some even thought
that Orson killed you.

98
00:06:05,300 --> 00:06:08,300
Well, that's sort of what
I wanted them to think.

99
00:06:08,600 --> 00:06:11,400
That's why I left my bird behind
and only took cash,

100
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:13,700
so they couldn't trace me
through my credit cards.

101
00:06:13,800 --> 00:06:15,900
So you
deliberately framed Orson?

102
00:06:16,700 --> 00:06:19,500
I'm not saying
it was my finest hour.

103
00:06:19,500 --> 00:06:22,800
But you have to understand,
Orson hurt me very badly.

104
00:06:22,800 --> 00:06:24,500
He cheated on me.

105
00:06:24,500 --> 00:06:26,800
Yes, I know--
with Monique polier.

106
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:29,700
And I thought,
if I disappeared,

107
00:06:29,800 --> 00:06:33,400
she'd get scared and leave him,
like he left me.

108
00:06:33,400 --> 00:06:35,500
Isn't jealousy awful?

109
00:06:35,500 --> 00:06:38,100
So why have you come back?

110
00:06:38,200 --> 00:06:39,500
I found
this fantastic therapist.

111
00:06:39,500 --> 00:06:42,900
He told me
that by holding on to my anger

112
00:06:42,900 --> 00:06:45,500
I was really just hurting
myself, which was hard to deny.

113
00:06:45,700 --> 00:06:46,600
I mean, hello,

114
00:06:46,700 --> 00:06:49,500
I'm here in Winnipeg
with a deaf aunt and no credit.

115
00:06:51,300 --> 00:06:54,400
So I thought,
it's time to make amends.

116
00:06:55,400 --> 00:06:56,300
Darling?

117
00:06:57,200 --> 00:07:01,100
Mrs McLean canceled, so...
I'm free for lunch.

118
00:07:01,900 --> 00:07:03,900
Um, actually,
we have a guest.

119
00:07:04,800 --> 00:07:06,300
<i>(Alma)</i> Hello, Orson.

120
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:07,700
Oh, hello...

121
00:07:09,600 --> 00:07:12,700
So... what is it
with you and redheads?

122
00:07:16,400 --> 00:07:18,700
<i>(bee buzzing)</i>

123
00:07:18,700 --> 00:07:21,700
I-I hope you don't mind me
springing this picnic on you.

124
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:24,200
I figured it'd be more fun
than some stuffy restaurant.

125
00:07:24,600 --> 00:07:28,000
Are you kidding?
What could be more romantic?

126
00:07:28,600 --> 00:07:30,300
Back off,
you son of a bitch!

127
00:07:31,300 --> 00:07:32,100
<i>(cell phone rings)</i>
more wine?

128
00:07:32,900 --> 00:07:34,000
Yes, keep it coming.

129
00:07:35,700 --> 00:07:36,700
Hello?

130
00:07:37,100 --> 00:07:38,900
<i>(chuckles)</i>
Hey, who's the dork?

131
00:07:39,200 --> 00:07:39,900
Carlos?

132
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:41,100
What's with that cap?

133
00:07:41,101 --> 00:07:42,101
"Extra! Extra! Read all about it!"

134
00:07:44,700 --> 00:07:45,700
Where the hell are you?

135
00:07:53,500 --> 00:07:55,600
What are you doing
at Mike's house?
- I live here.

136
00:07:56,100 --> 00:07:57,700
What do you mean you live there?
Since when?

137
00:07:57,900 --> 00:08:00,100
Gaby, my car's been
in the driveway for three weeks.

138
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:02,000
Even you can't be
that self-absorbed.

139
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:05,800
Well, as you can see,

140
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:08,000
I have more pleasant thing
to focus on.

141
00:08:09,700 --> 00:08:11,300
So when you gonna
tell Jimmy Olsen there

142
00:08:11,400 --> 00:08:12,300
that you hate picnics?

143
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:14,400
I'm gonna hang up now.

144
00:08:16,300 --> 00:08:18,000
So where were we?

145
00:08:18,300 --> 00:08:22,300
Your ex-husband
moved in across the street?

146
00:08:23,200 --> 00:08:24,200
What's that gonna be like?

147
00:08:24,700 --> 00:08:24,900
<i>(cell phone rings)</i>

148
00:08:26,700 --> 00:08:27,600
Yeah?!

149
00:08:27,700 --> 00:08:29,000
Are you gonna kiss him?

150
00:08:29,200 --> 00:08:30,500
That's right, Carlos.

151
00:08:30,700 --> 00:08:32,800
we <i>have</i> had some problems

152
00:08:32,900 --> 00:08:34,800
with raccoons getting
into the trash.

153
00:08:35,400 --> 00:08:37,500
so why don't you
just put a lid on it?

154
00:08:44,300 --> 00:08:46,300
okay, they're here.
Now listen, stand up.

155
00:08:46,400 --> 00:08:49,000
Kayla has been through a lot,
so when she walks in the door,

156
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:50,800
I want you to make her
feel welcome, okay?

157
00:08:50,800 --> 00:08:52,800
Give her a hug
and be really nice.

158
00:08:52,800 --> 00:08:56,200
I'm giving her my room.
How much nicer do I have to be?

159
00:08:56,300 --> 00:08:58,800
Well, nicer than that, or she's
gonna get alyour toys, too.

160
00:08:59,900 --> 00:09:00,900
<i>(Tom)</i> Hey, hey, hey!
Hi!

161
00:09:00,900 --> 00:09:04,300
Look who I found
wandering around the airport.

162
00:09:04,400 --> 00:09:06,700
Oh! Hi, Kayla! We missed you!

163
00:09:06,700 --> 00:09:08,600
We're so glad you're here.
<i>(laughs)</i>

164
00:09:12,700 --> 00:09:13,700
Okay, boys.

165
00:09:21,100 --> 00:09:23,600
Good. Yeah, okay.
So give her some room.

166
00:09:25,200 --> 00:09:27,900
Hey, wow, look,
are those presents for Kayla?

167
00:09:27,900 --> 00:09:29,600
Yes, they are.

168
00:09:30,400 --> 00:09:32,300
Hey, look at that.
Preston gave you a harmonica.

169
00:09:32,300 --> 00:09:33,600
Isn't that cool?

170
00:09:33,700 --> 00:09:36,600
Oh. "Harriet the spy."
Sounds mysterious.

171
00:09:36,900 --> 00:09:37,700
Thanks.

172
00:09:42,200 --> 00:09:44,100
And what did you get for Porter?

173
00:09:44,200 --> 00:09:47,600
A video game, but I get
to play it whenever I want.

174
00:09:47,900 --> 00:09:48,900
Porter!

175
00:09:51,900 --> 00:09:54,200
I--you know what?
I got you something, too.

176
00:09:55,400 --> 00:09:56,300
This...

177
00:09:57,400 --> 00:09:58,300
is Nellie.

178
00:09:59,700 --> 00:10:02,700
My grandma gave her to me
when I was little,

179
00:10:02,700 --> 00:10:06,900
and I was hoping you
could take care of her for me.

180
00:10:08,500 --> 00:10:09,500
Thanks.

181
00:10:12,600 --> 00:10:15,300
Hey, honey, why don't you
take your stuff and go upstairs

182
00:10:15,300 --> 00:10:17,100
and, uh, get ready
for lunch, okay?

183
00:10:17,100 --> 00:10:18,000
And I'll make some chili.

184
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:19,000
Okay, daddy.

185
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:23,700
Honey...

186
00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:27,600
that was so sweet...
to give her your doll.

187
00:10:28,200 --> 00:10:30,500
Oh. She didn't seem
that knocked out by it.

188
00:10:30,600 --> 00:10:33,700
Well, just give her some time.
She'll--she'll come around.

189
00:10:33,700 --> 00:10:34,900
It's a tough adjustment.

190
00:10:34,900 --> 00:10:35,600
Okay.

191
00:10:47,100 --> 00:10:48,100
I must say, Bree,

192
00:10:48,100 --> 00:10:51,300
I don't know when I've tasted
such moist pound cake.

193
00:10:52,500 --> 00:10:53,800
Sour cream.

194
00:10:55,300 --> 00:10:56,300
Ah.

195
00:11:01,500 --> 00:11:04,000
So whatever happened
to my parrot?

196
00:11:05,100 --> 00:11:06,300
I set it free.

197
00:11:06,400 --> 00:11:07,200
Mmm!

198
00:11:07,900 --> 00:11:10,000
Orson, they don't
fair well in the wild.

199
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:13,100
You should've--
- For God's sake, Alma,
who cares about the damn bird?

200
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:15,300
You set me up.

201
00:11:16,700 --> 00:11:18,400
Why don't I wrap up
a piece of this pound cake

202
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:19,800
for you to enjoy later?

203
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:24,900
Do you have any idea
what you put me through?

204
00:11:25,300 --> 00:11:26,800
You almost ruined my life.

205
00:11:26,900 --> 00:11:29,400
You've rebounded nicely.
Bree's lovely.

206
00:11:29,400 --> 00:11:30,700
Don't change the subject.

207
00:11:30,700 --> 00:11:34,800
You put me through a lot, too,
Orson, but I forgave you.

208
00:11:34,800 --> 00:11:36,700
Can't we just
put this behind us?

209
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:39,900
And that's all
you've come back for--closure?

210
00:11:39,900 --> 00:11:42,300
Of course. What else?

211
00:11:45,800 --> 00:11:47,900
I'm out of lipstick.
Can I borrow yours?

212
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:49,000
Sure.

213
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:53,900
Cherry berry?
- <i>(chuckles)</i> Austin likes
the way it tastes.

214
00:11:53,900 --> 00:11:56,100
Oh, I <i>so</i> did not need
to know that.

215
00:11:57,200 --> 00:11:58,600
So, um, where you going?

216
00:11:58,600 --> 00:12:00,500
Down to the jailhouse
to talk to Mike.

217
00:12:01,300 --> 00:12:04,100
But didn't you tell Ian
you wouldn't see him anymore?

218
00:12:04,600 --> 00:12:07,700
Yeah. But somebody's gotta
tell him about his new lawyer.

219
00:12:07,800 --> 00:12:09,800
Otherwise, the guy's gonna
show up, and he's gonna go,

220
00:12:09,800 --> 00:12:11,900
"who the hell is he?"
<i>(chuckles)</i> Ian gets that.

221
00:12:14,100 --> 00:12:16,700
Besides... why would it be
a big deal?

222
00:12:16,700 --> 00:12:18,000
Mike and I are over.

223
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:21,500
I was just wondering,
'cause, you know,

224
00:12:21,500 --> 00:12:23,600
You're putting on lipstick
to go to a prison.

225
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:30,200
Thank you
for clearing things up.

226
00:12:30,300 --> 00:12:34,100
Oh, well, it was
the least I could do.

227
00:12:34,100 --> 00:12:37,500
Orson, I'm truly sorry
for the pain I've caused,

228
00:12:37,500 --> 00:12:39,700
and if there's
anything else I can do...

229
00:12:42,700 --> 00:12:44,100
Actually, there is.

230
00:12:44,200 --> 00:12:46,900
I'd love it if you could join us
for dinner this weekend.

231
00:12:46,900 --> 00:12:48,900
There are some friends
that I'm just...

232
00:12:50,400 --> 00:12:52,300
dying for you to meet.

233
00:12:58,500 --> 00:12:59,800
You got me a lawyer?

234
00:12:59,900 --> 00:13:01,800
Yeah, and he is fantastic.

235
00:13:01,800 --> 00:13:04,700
You cannot believe
the scum he has gotten off.

236
00:13:06,100 --> 00:13:07,500
<i>not that you're scum.</i>

237
00:13:08,100 --> 00:13:10,200
But, you know, if you were,
you'd be sitting pretty.

238
00:13:11,100 --> 00:13:13,400
I'm paying you back--
every penny.

239
00:13:13,400 --> 00:13:16,700
Oh, well, you know,
we'll figure that out later.

240
00:13:16,700 --> 00:13:18,400
I-I can't believe that

241
00:13:18,400 --> 00:13:21,000
I just listened to all that
stuff Edie told me about you,

242
00:13:21,100 --> 00:13:24,200
and it turns out you're
the only one standing by me.

243
00:13:26,100 --> 00:13:28,300
You're a good friend,
Susan.

244
00:13:29,700 --> 00:13:32,600
Um, yeah, about that...

245
00:13:33,900 --> 00:13:34,600
It's Ian.

246
