501
00:27:07,500 --> 00:27:09,400
<i>(laughs)</i> Kayla,
I'm not fooling around.

502
00:27:09,800 --> 00:27:10,900
We--we're going.

503
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:15,400
Mm-hmm. Okay.

504
00:27:16,300 --> 00:27:19,200
Boys, go to the car.
I'll be out in a minute. Go.

505
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:29,000
Listen, sweetheart, I don't
blame you for being angry.

506
00:27:29,100 --> 00:27:32,800
Your mom's gone,
and you're stuck with me.

507
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:35,500
But...

508
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:43,200
the last thing
she said to me was,

509
00:27:43,200 --> 00:27:45,000
"promise
you'll take care of Kayla,"

510
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:46,700
and I am going to.

511
00:27:48,100 --> 00:27:49,700
But you're gonna
have to help me, okay?

512
00:27:53,500 --> 00:27:55,000
We can leave when I'm done.

513
00:28:04,700 --> 00:28:05,800
Okay, let's go.

514
00:28:06,900 --> 00:28:08,700
<i>(screaming)</i>
Hey, whoa!
Whoa, whoa, whoa! Okay.

515
00:28:08,700 --> 00:28:11,400
What the hell are you doing?!
Stop, stop! Stop screaming!

516
00:28:11,400 --> 00:28:12,700
Stop!
Leave me alone!

517
00:28:12,700 --> 00:28:15,200
You're not my mommy!

518
00:28:34,100 --> 00:28:34,900
Oh.

519
00:28:44,300 --> 00:28:45,400
Guys, how would you like

520
00:28:45,400 --> 00:28:46,900
to eat dinner
in front of the television

521
00:28:46,900 --> 00:28:48,900
for a whole week?

522
00:28:57,200 --> 00:28:59,300
What are you guys
doing here?

523
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:05,600
Kayla, stop screaming!
You're hurting my ears!

524
00:29:05,700 --> 00:29:07,900
Get in the car!
- <i>(Kayla)</i> Aah!

525
00:29:08,400 --> 00:29:11,000
Come on!
We're going home!
- Aah!

526
00:29:11,100 --> 00:29:12,600
Get your seat belt on!

527
00:29:12,900 --> 00:29:15,300
Kids--
they're always roughhousing.

528
00:29:35,800 --> 00:29:36,900
Why'd you stop?

529
00:29:38,200 --> 00:29:41,800
Well, uh, it's getting late.
I got your blouse unbuttoned.

530
00:29:41,900 --> 00:29:43,800
That's usually when
we call it a night.

531
00:29:45,400 --> 00:29:47,300
Do you wanna
call it a night?

532
00:29:48,500 --> 00:29:50,400
What, do you wanna
grab a pizza or something?

533
00:29:59,200 --> 00:30:01,700
I wanna do what...
You wanna do.

534
00:30:02,900 --> 00:30:04,500
Well...

535
00:30:04,800 --> 00:30:06,000
You know what I wanna do.

536
00:30:08,500 --> 00:30:09,600
Well, okay.

537
00:30:10,900 --> 00:30:12,000
Are you sure?

538
00:30:13,700 --> 00:30:14,900
Yeah, I'm sure.

539
00:30:35,900 --> 00:30:37,100
You can always
spot the new guys

540
00:30:37,100 --> 00:30:39,000
by the way
they pick through their food.

541
00:30:42,500 --> 00:30:44,600
So what did you do when
you thought no one was looking?

542
00:30:46,100 --> 00:30:47,900
Cops say I killed a woman.

543
00:30:48,300 --> 00:30:49,600
But you didn't, right?

544
00:30:51,700 --> 00:30:54,200
Actually, I have no idea.

545
00:30:55,800 --> 00:30:57,800
Got pretty banged up in an accident.

546
00:30:58,500 --> 00:31:00,800
Last two years are blank.

547
00:31:01,500 --> 00:31:04,300
Well, that's a fresh approach.

548
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:07,000
Not sure the jury's gonna swallow it.

549
00:31:07,300 --> 00:31:08,300
It's the truth.

550
00:31:11,500 --> 00:31:12,700
I believe you.

551
00:31:17,300 --> 00:31:19,700
OK. Mrs McCluskey's downstairs,

552
00:31:19,700 --> 00:31:22,200
and we will be right across the street
if you need us.

553
00:31:22,200 --> 00:31:23,300
OK, daddy.

554
00:31:25,500 --> 00:31:28,300
You know, I heard what happened
with Lynette today.

555
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:33,100
Hey, she is doing her best.
Why are you being so hard on her?

556
00:31:33,400 --> 00:31:35,800
'Cause it's her fault my mommy died.

557
00:31:36,100 --> 00:31:37,900
No. No, honey, it's not.

558
00:31:37,900 --> 00:31:39,400
Mom only went to that store

559
00:31:39,400 --> 00:31:41,300
Because Lynette was trying to steal me.

560
00:31:41,300 --> 00:31:42,800
No. That is not true.

561
00:31:43,600 --> 00:31:45,400
Look, honey,

562
00:31:45,400 --> 00:31:47,500
it is way more complicated than that.

563
00:31:49,100 --> 00:31:50,900
I know you miss your mommy.

564
00:31:50,900 --> 00:31:53,100
And she loved you very much.

565
00:31:53,800 --> 00:31:55,000
But guess what:

566
00:31:56,400 --> 00:31:58,100
Lynette loves you too.

567
00:32:00,200 --> 00:32:02,100
That's why you gotta
give her a chance.

568
00:32:03,200 --> 00:32:04,500
Can you do that for me?

569
00:32:07,500 --> 00:32:09,200
OK. I'll be good.

570
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:11,500
That's my girl!

571
00:32:13,100 --> 00:32:15,000
But I'm never gonna love her.

572
00:32:16,300 --> 00:32:17,900
And you can't make me.

573
00:32:32,700 --> 00:32:34,000
Well, you've won.

574
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:36,000
What did I win?

575
00:32:40,300 --> 00:32:41,800
Bill and I split up.

576
00:32:42,400 --> 00:32:43,800
Can't say I'm surprised.

577
00:32:44,700 --> 00:32:46,000
He wasn't right for you.

578
00:32:46,500 --> 00:32:47,300
I know.

579
00:32:48,700 --> 00:32:51,300
So just admit
you sent the flowers.

580
00:32:52,300 --> 00:32:53,600
I didn't.

581
00:32:54,200 --> 00:32:56,300
Carlos, just tell me.

582
00:32:56,300 --> 00:32:58,400
I won't be mad.
I promise.

583
00:32:59,700 --> 00:33:01,000
gaby, if I was gonna
send you flowers,

584
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:02,800
I wouldn't send you
pink roses.

585
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:05,700
I'd send you white orchids,

586
00:33:05,800 --> 00:33:07,600
because I know
they're your favorite.

587
00:33:09,500 --> 00:33:12,500
And if I wanted
to cheer you up--sunflowers.

588
00:33:12,800 --> 00:33:14,100
And for the flu...

589
00:33:16,100 --> 00:33:17,300
blue irises.

590
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:31,800
I hate
that you know me so well,

591
00:33:32,400 --> 00:33:34,200
and it took so long
for that to happen.

592
00:33:34,200 --> 00:33:36,700
Now I have to start over again
with somebody else.

593
00:33:37,400 --> 00:33:40,100
Yeah.
That's what dating's for.

594
00:33:40,200 --> 00:33:42,000
I know, and it sucks.

595
00:33:43,200 --> 00:33:44,000
<i>(laughs)</i>
I mean, you saw me.

596
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:46,200
I went on a picnic
and ate pudding out of a can.

597
00:33:46,200 --> 00:33:47,200
It was horrible.

598
00:33:49,700 --> 00:33:51,200
<i>(sighs)</i> well, if it makes you
feel any better,

599
00:33:51,200 --> 00:33:53,600
I got dragged to the ballet
the other night.

600
00:33:55,400 --> 00:33:56,900
so you <i>are</i> dating.

601
00:33:58,800 --> 00:34:01,500
That's why you've been
lifting weights and jogging.

602
00:34:01,800 --> 00:34:04,300
Well, if you wanna
bag the big game,

603
00:34:05,300 --> 00:34:06,700
gotta work on the guns.

604
00:34:12,100 --> 00:34:13,400
I'll give you this--

605
00:34:15,200 --> 00:34:17,500
You're gonna be
a tough act to follow, Carlos.

606
00:34:23,700 --> 00:34:25,000
Back at ya, babe.

607
00:34:41,100 --> 00:34:43,000
I'm so sorry
to keep you waiting,

608
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:44,200
but I don't want
to introduce you

609
00:34:44,200 --> 00:34:47,000
until all my guests
are here.
- I don't mind.

610
00:34:48,100 --> 00:34:49,600
By the way, um,

611
00:34:50,400 --> 00:34:53,100
when my friends
ask you what happened--

612
00:34:53,100 --> 00:34:54,100
and they will--

613
00:34:54,700 --> 00:34:57,200
I don't think it's necessary
to go into all that

614
00:34:57,300 --> 00:35:00,200
unpleasantness
about Orson and Monique.

615
00:35:00,200 --> 00:35:01,100
All they need to know

616
00:35:01,100 --> 00:35:03,900
is that you're back
and we're on good terms.

617
00:35:04,200 --> 00:35:06,000
And Orson didn't kill me.

618
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:09,100
And Orson didn't kill you.

619
00:35:11,400 --> 00:35:13,800
Oh, okay, just one minute.
That'll be Susan.

620
00:35:36,900 --> 00:35:39,300
Hi. I brought you
a Bundt cake.

621
00:35:39,300 --> 00:35:40,700
Don't worry.
I didn't make it.

622
00:35:40,700 --> 00:35:43,100
Oh, you didn't have to do that.
- I was really touched.

623
00:35:43,100 --> 00:35:45,200
It was so big of you.

624
00:35:45,200 --> 00:35:48,100
Well, when you're wrong,
you're wrong.

625
00:35:51,600 --> 00:35:52,800
Now that we're all assembled,

626
00:35:52,800 --> 00:35:55,400
I'd like to introduce
the guest of honor.

627
00:35:55,500 --> 00:35:58,800
I hope you'll all be as
delighted to meet her as I was.

628
00:35:59,600 --> 00:36:00,700
You can come in now.

629
00:36:05,700 --> 00:36:08,200
Everyone, this is Alma Hodge.

630
00:36:08,600 --> 00:36:10,000
Orson's first wife.

631
00:36:14,600 --> 00:36:16,600
Oh, about that apology...

632
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:18,100
Any time you're ready.

633
00:36:21,100 --> 00:36:23,800
So you have been in Canada
this entire time?

634
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:26,400
Well, my aunt Agnes
has a place in Winnipeg.

635
00:36:26,400 --> 00:36:28,300
I hadn't planned
on staying so long,

636
00:36:28,300 --> 00:36:32,900
but I needed the time to find myself.
- It would've been nice if someone could have found you.

637
00:36:32,900 --> 00:36:35,700
There was a whole lot
of drama around here.
- Yes, I heard.

638
00:36:35,700 --> 00:36:38,500
People actually thought
Orson had done away with me?

639
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:41,100
Amazing, isn't it,

640
00:36:41,100 --> 00:36:43,100
where some people's minds
will go?

641
00:36:46,600 --> 00:36:49,400
Well, you gotta hand it to her.
Just when you think

642
00:36:49,400 --> 00:36:51,300
Bree's thrown
every conceivable theme party,

643
00:36:51,300 --> 00:36:52,600
she hosts a "Shame on you

644
00:36:52,600 --> 00:36:56,700
for thinking my husband
killed someone" dinner.
- So Alma's alive. Big deal.

645
00:36:56,800 --> 00:36:59,300
We still don't know what went
down between Orson and Monique.
<i>(doorbell rings)</i>

646
00:36:59,300 --> 00:37:02,200
Susan, please. We look stupid
enough for suspecting him.

647
00:37:02,200 --> 00:37:03,300
Just let it go.

648
00:37:07,600 --> 00:37:09,500
It may be a little late
for that.

649
00:37:10,600 --> 00:37:13,000
Detective Ridley.
Can I help you?

650
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:15,200
Yes. I'd like
to speak to your husband.

651
00:37:16,700 --> 00:37:18,300
Oh, well,
I'm afraid he's not here,

652
00:37:18,300 --> 00:37:21,200
but I will be happy to tell him
that you came by.

653
00:37:21,300 --> 00:37:22,700
<i>(Orson)</i> who is it, darling?

654
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:28,100
<i>(sighs)</i> excuse us.

655
00:37:31,100 --> 00:37:33,600
Can't this wait?
We're having a dinner party.

656
00:37:35,300 --> 00:37:36,500
<i>(Detective Ridley)</i>
hello, dr. Hodge.

657
00:37:36,800 --> 00:37:38,000
Detective Ridley.

658
00:37:38,100 --> 00:37:40,300
We need you to come with us.
We have some questions

659
00:37:40,300 --> 00:37:45,600
about that Jane Doe
we showed you in the morgue.
- Why do you think I'd know anything about her?

660
00:37:45,600 --> 00:37:48,700
well, you <i>were</i> having an affair
with her when she died.

661
00:37:50,800 --> 00:37:52,300
Oh, where did you
hear that?

662
00:37:57,400 --> 00:37:58,400
Susan?

663
00:38:00,100 --> 00:38:02,300
I didn't know
they were gonna come tonight.

664
00:38:04,500 --> 00:38:07,000
Uh, I'm happy to answer
any questions

665
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:08,300
that you might have.

666
00:38:08,300 --> 00:38:11,400
My apologies. Please, stay.
Enjoy the dessert.

667
00:38:15,900 --> 00:38:17,400
I don't believe this.

668
00:38:17,400 --> 00:38:19,100
You called the police?

669
00:38:19,100 --> 00:38:21,000
Well, obviously,
you weren't going to.

670
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:24,000
They needed to know that that
dead woman was Orson's mistress.

671
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:27,000
I told you that
in confidence.
- Did you seriously think

672
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:30,300
I could sit on information
that would exonerate Mike?

673
00:38:30,400 --> 00:38:33,300
I mean, if you had seen his face
in jail the other day...

674
00:38:33,400 --> 00:38:35,700
The other day?
You--you saw Mike?

675
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:39,200
Yeah. I've just to tell him
about the lawyer.

676
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:41,900
I <i>know</i>
that Mike is innocent.

677
00:38:41,900 --> 00:38:44,200
Right, just like you knew
she was dead.

678
00:38:45,600 --> 00:38:47,300
I thought
we had an agreement.

679
00:38:47,400 --> 00:38:50,000
We do. Can we talk
about this later?

680
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:50,800
When?

681
00:38:51,400 --> 00:38:53,400
After your next
conjugal visit?

682
00:38:54,300 --> 00:38:55,800
Ian. Wait!

683
00:38:55,900 --> 00:38:58,900
Boy, when it comes to Mike,
there's no one you won't betray.

684
00:38:59,300 --> 00:39:00,400
Excuse me?

685
00:39:01,100 --> 00:39:02,200
Hey, guys...

686
00:39:02,200 --> 00:39:03,600
Please leave my house.

687
00:39:03,600 --> 00:39:05,900
Bree!
- You heard me. Get out!

688
00:39:06,200 --> 00:39:07,900
Okay, Bree,
I know you're angry,

689
00:39:07,900 --> 00:39:09,200
but for the sake
of our friendship--

690
00:39:09,200 --> 00:39:12,900
Oh, make no mistake,
our friendship is over.

691
00:39:19,300 --> 00:39:21,300
Okay. You go...

692
00:39:21,300 --> 00:39:22,300
Okay.

693
00:39:29,300 --> 00:39:30,600
So, Winnipeg...

694
00:39:32,300 --> 00:39:34,000
must get pretty cold
up there.

695
00:39:38,600 --> 00:39:42,000
I'm just getting my coat.
- Ian, please, I just lost
one of my best friends.

696
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:45,100
I can't lose you, too.
- You said that
you wouldn't see him again.

697
00:39:45,200 --> 00:39:47,600
But you had to know
that I would go one more time

698
00:39:47,600 --> 00:39:50,100
to just explain everything.
- Actually, no, I didn't.

699
00:39:50,100 --> 00:39:52,000
Well, that's just crazy!

700
00:39:52,100 --> 00:39:54,000
Why are you acting like
a crazy person?

701
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:56,700
Because you've already
left me once for this--this guy!

702
00:39:57,000 --> 00:39:59,300
Things are different now!
I-I love you!

703
00:39:59,300 --> 00:40:01,600
You--you don't have
to worry about that anymore.

704
00:40:02,300 --> 00:40:03,800
If we're gonna
make this relationship work,

705
00:40:03,800 --> 00:40:07,600
then you have to trust me,
and why are you smiling at me?

706
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:10,600
You just said
that you love me.
- Yeah? So?

707
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:13,500
Well, you've never
said that before.
- Yes, I have.

708
00:40:13,500 --> 00:40:15,300
No. I-I-I would've
remembered.

709
00:40:15,300 --> 00:40:17,100
Well, I'm saying it now.
I love you.

710
00:40:17,100 --> 00:40:19,700
Do you have
a problem with that?
- No, ma'am.

711
00:40:19,700 --> 00:40:22,100
You--you--you can't kiss me now.
I'm yelling at you.

712
00:40:22,100 --> 00:40:23,100
Well, I'm listening.

713
00:40:23,100 --> 00:40:25,500
Well... <i>(sighs)</i>
don't--don't think that you can

714
00:40:25,500 --> 00:40:27,400
get out of this,
you know, by just...

715
00:40:28,300 --> 00:40:31,900
Oh, God. Oh, yeah, uh,
oh, yeah, right--right there.

716
00:40:31,900 --> 00:40:32,900
Oh, right there. <i>(gasps)</i>

717
00:40:37,200 --> 00:40:39,600
Look, I think
we should stop doing this.

718
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:42,900
I know it's my idea,

719
00:40:42,900 --> 00:40:45,800
but it just doesn't
feel right anymore.

720
00:40:47,700 --> 00:40:50,000
You slept with Julie.
It's no big deal.

721
00:40:50,800 --> 00:40:52,000
Well, it is to her,

722
00:40:52,100 --> 00:40:53,400
and I don't want
to see her get hurt.

723
00:40:53,400 --> 00:40:54,800
Me, either.

724
00:40:56,300 --> 00:40:57,900
<i>(whispers)</i>
so let's just not tell her.

725
00:41:04,800 --> 00:41:07,500
<i>(Edie)</i> there's no place in
fairview that's more peaceful.

726
00:41:07,800 --> 00:41:09,700
All the floors are hardwood.

727
00:41:09,800 --> 00:41:11,900
Oh, there are
brand-new appliances.

728
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:13,300
And the gardens are...

729
00:41:13,900 --> 00:41:15,000
well, they're beautiful.

730
00:41:16,400 --> 00:41:18,600
So... what do you think?

731
00:41:21,300 --> 00:41:22,400
I'll take it.

732
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:25,800
Really?
<i>(chuckles)</i> That's terrific!

733
00:41:25,800 --> 00:41:27,700
I'll draw up the papers
in the morning.

734
00:41:32,600 --> 00:41:34,500
If you
don't mind me asking,

735
00:41:34,800 --> 00:41:37,800
why were you so interested
in this particular street?

736
00:41:38,100 --> 00:41:41,100
I've been moving around a lot
in the last few months,

737
00:41:41,400 --> 00:41:44,100
and I need a place
where I can really settle down.

738
00:41:44,100 --> 00:41:45,300
You know what I mean?

739
00:41:46,400 --> 00:41:48,400
<i>(Alma)</i>
I wanna live in a place

740
00:41:50,100 --> 00:41:53,900
where people still have 
some sense of moral value

741
00:41:53,900 --> 00:41:57,200
and where friendships are good and strong

742
00:41:57,200 --> 00:41:59,900
and last forever.

743
00:42:01,600 --> 00:42:03,100
That's what I'm looking for.

744
00:42:04,400 --> 00:42:07,400
Then I think Wisteria Lane is the place for you.

745
00:42:08,700 --> 00:42:09,400
Good.

746
00:42:10,100 --> 00:42:12,300
More than anything, 
I just want to fit in.

747
00:42:15,100 --> 00:42:17,100
<i>Oh, you will, Alma.</i>

748
00:42:17,100 --> 00:42:19,400
<i>You absolutely will.</i>

